          "title": "The Anakim — the fear that could not stand",
          "body": "The chapter's final military notice (11:21-22) is placed last for maximum narrative effect. The Anakim — the giant clan whose mere existence had produced the catastrophic unbelief of Numbers 13 ('we were like grasshoppers in our own sight,' Numbers 13:33) — are cut off by Joshua from the entire hill country. Hebron, Debir, Anab: every stronghold where the Anakim had concentrated their presence is now destroyed. The narrator records with precision that 'no Anakim were left in the land of the sons of Israel' — the very land whose possession they had made impossible in the spy-generation's reckoning. Only in Gaza, Gath, and Ashdod — Philistine coastal cities outside the full conquest perimeter — do survivors remain. The reader familiar with the forward narrative knows that Gath will produce Goliath (1 Samuel 17:4), which means Joshua 11:22 is not a footnote but a narrative thread — the conquest's unfinished business, left for a later, greater obedience."
